{
  "comment_text": {
    "sn43.15:1.1": "Nibbāna is the truth since delusion has ceased (<a href='https://suttacentral.net/mn140/en/sujato#26.2'>MN 140:26.2</a>). ",
    "sn43.16:1.1": "This is a common metaphor, eg. <a href='https://suttacentral.net/snp5.18/en/sujato#1.3'>Snp 5.18:1.3</a>. ",
    "sn43.17:1.1": "For this term and the next, see <a href='https://suttacentral.net/dhp36/en/sujato#1'>Dhp 36:1</a>, <a href='https://suttacentral.net/thag2.46/en/sujato#2.3'>Thag 2.46:2.3</a>. ",
    "sn43.19:1.1": "“Undecrepit” (<i lang='pi' translate='no'>ajajjara</i>) doesn’t appear elsewhere in Pali. However, Buddhist Sanskrit texts sometimes use <i lang='pi' translate='no'>jarjara</i> (“decrepitude”) in definitions of old age in dependent origination (Nidānasaṁyukta 16.15, Pratītyasamutpādavibhaṅgasūtra 15b, Pratītyasamutpādādivibhaṅganirdeśasūtra 118, Dharmaskandha 16v2). ",
    "sn43.20:1.1": "“Everlasting” (<i lang='pi' translate='no'>dhuva</i>) is normally a synonym of “permanent” (<i lang='pi' translate='no'>nicca</i>). It is used of Brahmā (<a href='https://suttacentral.net/sn6.4/en/sujato#1.4'>SN 6.4:1.4</a>), and of Nibbāna at <a href='https://suttacentral.net/iti43/en/sujato#4.4'>Iti 43:4.4</a>. ",
    "sn43.21:1.1": "“Not worn out” (<i lang='pi' translate='no'>apalokita</i>) is apparently unique in this sense. “Wearing out” (<i lang='pi' translate='no'>paloka</i>) is a characteristic of conditioned things (<a href='https://suttacentral.net/sn35.84/en/sujato#2.3'>SN 35.84:2.3</a>). ",
    "sn43.22:1.1": "Normally <i lang='pi' translate='no'>anidassana</i> means “invisible” (<a href='https://suttacentral.net/dn33/en/sujato#1.10.76'>DN 33:1.10.76</a>) or “formless” (<a href='https://suttacentral.net/mn21/en/sujato#14.8'>MN 21:14.8</a>), although it is sometimes interpreted to mean Nibbāna (<a href='https://suttacentral.net/dn11/en/sujato#85.18'>DN 11:85.18</a>). While Nibbāna is, of course, formless and invisible, I believe this is the only place <i lang='pi' translate='no'>anidassana</i> unambiguously refers to Nibbāna. ",
    "sn43.23:1.1": "<a href='https://suttacentral.net/an6.15/en/sujato#6.2'>AN 6.15:6.2</a>, <a href='https://suttacentral.net/dhp254/en/sujato#4'>Dhp 254:4</a>. ",
    "sn43.27:1.1": "<i lang='pi' translate='no'>Siva</i>, see <a href='https://suttacentral.net/sn2.21/en/sujato'>SN 2.21</a> and notes. ",
    "sn43.28:1.1": "<a href='https://suttacentral.net/sn7.11/en/sujato#6.2'>SN 7.11:6.2</a>. ",
    "sn43.30:1.1": "This term and the next are commonly used of individuals who have realized Nibbāna (<a href='https://suttacentral.net/an6.46/en/sujato#6.5'>AN 6.46:6.5</a>, <a href='https://suttacentral.net/sn51.22/en/sujato#2.2'>SN 51.22:2.2</a>). ",
    "sn43.32:1.1": "<a href='https://suttacentral.net/snp5.19/en/sujato#7.3'>Snp 5.19:7.3</a>. ",
    "sn43.35:1.1": "Normally a term for the mind developed through love, etc. (<a href='https://suttacentral.net/mn21/en/sujato#11.14'>MN 21:11.14</a>), or for good acts with pleasant outcomes (<a href='https://suttacentral.net/an3.23/en/sujato#2.1'>AN 3.23:2.1</a>, <a href='https://suttacentral.net/mn57/en/sujato#9.2'>MN 57:9.2</a>). ",
    "sn43.39:1.1": "“Not clinging” (<i lang='pi' translate='no'>anālaya</i>) is part of the standard definition of the third noble truth (<a href='https://suttacentral.net/sn56.11/en/sujato#4.7'>SN 56.11:4.7</a>). ",
    "sn43.40:1.1": "<a href='https://suttacentral.net/snp5.11/en/sujato#3.2'>Snp 5.11:3.2</a>. | This series of terms is used of the Buddha (<a href='https://suttacentral.net/sn42.7/en/sujato'>SN 42.7</a>) or one’s own good deeds (<a href='https://suttacentral.net/an3.51/en/sujato#2.4'>AN 3.51:2.4</a>). "
  },
